Last Call for Papers: Workshop on Computational Modeling of Lexical=20
Acquisition - The Split Meeting -

http://www.ohz.unist.hr/cpala/

Time: 25.-28. July 2005
Location: University of Split, Croatia

Abstract submission deadline: March 23rd 2005

The Croatian Language Technologies Society (CLTS) and the University of=20=

Split are pleased to sponsor the inaugural meeting of the Workshop on=20
Computational Linguistics held in Split, Croatia, focusing on the topic=20=

of "Computational Modeling of Lexical Acquisition". We will build on=20
the topics in formal-theoretical and computational linguistics, in=20
particular on issues in learnability, complexity and modeling of=20
lexical knowledge.

This workshop is especially intended to provide a forum for the=20
presentation of unique and original research on computational=20
linguistic topics in the domain of learning of lexical properties, i.e.=20=

lexical acquisition, including but not limited to the following topics:

a. machine learning methods for lexical acquisition
- speech and language segmentation into lexical units
- induction and learning of phonological and morphological structure
- inducing formal grammars from discovered structural properties
- learning lexical semantic properties and lexical disambiguation
- computational models of psycholinguistic aspects of lexical=20
acquisition

b. corpora, evaluation and applications
- induction of part-of-speech information for tagging and automatic=20
annotation (via e.g. clustering and classification, using Vector Space=20=

Modeling or other strategies)
- corpora for learning phonological and morphological regularities and=20=

a common gold standard
- applications using machine learning and automatic lexical acquisition=20=

(e.g. tagger, ontologies, textmining)
- evaluation strategies and methods for learning approaches

This workshop will expand into a fixed annual event organized by the=20
Croatian Language Technologies Society (CLTS) to be hosted, in turn,=20
and shared among all interested and committed Croatian Universities.

We strongly encourage students to participate at this workshop and join=20=

the tutorial sessions!

Tutorials:
- Thomas Hanneforth (University of Potsdam) "Finite State Modeling and=20=

the Potsdam FSMLib"
- Damir =C4=86avar (Indiana University) "Vector Space Modeling, Latent=20=

Semantic Analysis, Clustering Algorithms for Lexical Acquisition"

Mail your suggestions for additional tutorials that you would volunteer=20=

to teach to:  cpala@ohz.unist.hr

Publications:
Papers and presentations will be published online and on a CD-ROM=20
distributed during the workshop. All tutorial material, necessary=20
programs and example code will be published on the workshop CD-ROM as=20
well.
Publishers will be approached for publication of the proceedings.  If=20
you are interested or have suggestions, please contact: =20
cpala@ohz.unist.hr

Detailed instructions on abstract submission and registration can be=20
found on the following web page:

http://www.ohz.unist.hr/cpala/


